The Central Bank has received a double burden from Congress: maximising the employment rate in the US and maintaining price stability.
But since the great economic crisis, Fed leaders have confirmed that there is a third unwritten task: financial stability.
And this third task could be factor X in a decision that is too difficult to anticipate, which will be announced Tuesday, and will determine whether the US economy is ready to be disbursed by the unprecedented incentive offered by the short-term interest rate almost zero in force since the end of 2008.
Even if most data indicate a strong growing economy, the recent turmoil in global financial markets could scare Fed officials already cautious of adding volatility by increasing the reference rate to federal funds - even with only one quarter percentage point.
