Weight reduction surgery may be useful for mild obesity diabetics
The benefits of weight reduction surgery in patients with mild obesity, type 2 diabetes may be maintained for at least five years, according to a new study.
It is still premature to say whether mildly obese diabetics live more after weight loss surgery than those who undergo non-surgical treatments.
"It takes a lot of time to centralize mortality data," said Dr. Robin Blackstone, a specialist in obesity surgery, because she wrote an article about the new study in JAMA Surgery.
Weight loss operations, called bariatric surgery, use different methods to reduce the stomach.
They reduce the feeling of hunger and limit the body's ability to absorb food.
Throughout the years, bariatric surgery has proven to be effective in the treatment of type 2 diabetes, but most studies have been performed on people with morbid obesity with a body mass index (BMI) 35 or higher.
BMI, a weight measurement unit relative to height, is considered normal within 18.5-24.9.
The BMI value of at least 25 indicates that a person is overweight and individuals with BMI over 30 are considered obese.
You can calculate the BMI by accessing: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For the new study, scientists from Taiwan's General Min-Sheng Hospital used the data collected after 2007 in a trial comparing two types of bariatric surgery - gastric bypass and manchu gastrectomy - in medical treatment of type 2 diabetes to people with mild obesity.
Mean BMI in people who underwent surgery decreased from 31 to 24.5 to the end of the fifth year in the study.
In the meantime, BMI in people who received non-surgical treatments against diabetes has remained close to the same level, i.e. 29.
Of those who had surgery, diabetes completely healed 36% and partially 28%.
In the group treated by medical methods, by comparison, diabetes completely healed only 1% and partially to only 2% of subjects.
In addition, the control of blood pressure, triglycerides and LDL "red" cholesterol "have generally been better in the surgical group", concluded the authors.
Researchers also monitored the blood level of haemoglobin A1c, which reflects the level of blood glucose over time.
Researchers write that the optimal level of haemoglobin A1c is below 7%.
Following surgery, the mean haemoglobin level A1c decreased from approximately 9% to approximately 6%.
But in the group treated by medical methods, it remained about 8%.
However, this improved "glycaemic control" - reflected by improved haemoglobin levels A1c - did not reduce the mortality rate to five years, according to chief researcher Dr. Chih-Cheng Hsu and colleagues.
The research team also compared the average results associated with the two types of surgery.
In the fifth year, compared with the manchu gastrectomy group, the bypass surgery group lost more weight (18.7 versus 14.2 kg), recorded more significant decreases in BMI (7.4 versus 5.1) and haemoglobin A1c (3.1% versus 2.1%), and showed a higher likelihood of complete remission of diabetes (46.9% versus 16.7%).
Although the new study does not indicate a benefit in survival or surgery after five years, there is evidence from a study carried out on high-weight people in Sweden that surgery prolongs life, says Blackstone, from Arizona University, Faculty of Medicine - Phoenix.
In the Swedish study, obese people who underwent bariatric surgery showed a probability of approximately 29% lower to die after 15 years compared with a group that tried more conventional methods.
Although the new study did not indicate a survival benefit for patients who underwent surgery, Blackstone said it is an optimistic aspect for people with BMI under 35 procedural interests.
"This is the point where this work is critical because it claims that this surgery is safe in the lower BMI group", without increasing the risk of death or kidney disease, she says.
Blackstone added that patients and doctors should start taking the weight seriously then the patient's BMI reaches 27-30.
"I think we wait too long until we encourage people to take this seriously," she said.
