The government approved, on Wednesday, "The National Immigration Strategy for the period 2015-2018" and "The Action Plan for the Year in Progress", documents considered "to be still a stage in Romania's efforts to modernise the immigration management process in the national territory", according to a press release.
The above-mentioned source shows that the strategy aims to effectively manage the phenomenon of immigration, including general strategic objectives, specific objectives and action guidelines that reflect policies at European level adapted to national realities.
In view of the problems facing the States of the immediate vicinity of Romania, measures are being taken to manage the unitary and consistent situations caused by the possible emergence of an influx of illegal immigrants in Romania, generated by situations of political, social, economic or military nature.
"Roman authorities will contribute to the creation of a flexible admission system, but at the same time will pay special attention to citizens from countries with potential migration or which may affect national security," adds the recalled source.
The strategy identifies a number of factors that can influence immigration and asylum, including maintaining the conflict situation in Syria, reactivating the conflict in Iraq, maintaining an unstable situation in the neighbouring areas of Romania (Ukraine, Transnistria), perpetuating and growing in intensity of the Israeli-Palestinian armed conflict.
On the other hand, the document sets out and some general strategic objectives related to immigration, such as: promoting legal migration, more rigorous checks on the legality of the headquarters of third-country nationals in Romania and the corresponding application of removal and restrictive measures, improving the national asylum system.
The national strategy also includes specific objectives relevant to the transposition and implementation of the general strategic objectives.
These include: facilitating access to the territory of Romania of third-party citizens who meet the needs of employment, favouring the access of third-country nationals to Romanian higher education institutions for the areas and professions identified as deficit.
With regard to the 2015 Action Plan, the Government appreciated that it represents "a means by which concrete activities are established that will lead to the creation of a flexible system to stop the migration phenomenon growing".
Romania, in a European top on the labour market
Latvia, Romania and Bulgaria recorded the large increase in the total labour costs of the European Union Member States in the second quarter of the year compared to the similar period in 2014, according to data published on Wednesday by the European Statistical Office (Eurostat).
