The only EU states where the hourly cost of the labour force fell in quarter two of this year were Greece (minus 2.9%), Cyprus (minus 1.2%) and Italy (minus 0.4%).
The advancement of labour-force costs in Romania from April to June 2015 is mainly due to the increase in the hourly cost of the labour force in industry and services, with 7.9% and 7.6% respectively.
In the construction sector, Romania recorded an advance of 5.8% of the hourly cost of the labor force.
